li.p:
We view the vectors as the columns of a matrix so that
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since there is a column without a pivot position, the vectors must be linearly dependent. We also expect this because four vectors in \real^3 must always be linearly dependent.

If we view the first three columns as an augmented matrix, we have
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
We see that \vvec_3 = 2\vvec_1-\vvec_2.

Viewing the vectors as the columns of a matrix, we have
\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ -1 \amp 2 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since there is a pivot position in every column, the vectors are linearly independent.

We construct the matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 2 \amp 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -2 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp k \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp k-3 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
If the vectors are linearly dependent, we cannot have a pivot position in the third column. This means that k=3.

We have
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 2 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 7 \\ -1 \amp 2 \amp 6 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that \vvec_3 = -2\vvec_1+2\vvec_2 and so \laspan{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3,\vvec_4} = \laspan{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_4}.
